    <segment id="1" parent="16" relname="background">
Interesting thoughts on error recovery.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="span"> Just to keep the debate alive, why should we see error messages such as &quot;Windows has recovered from a serious error.&quot;?</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="3" relname="circumstance"> When the system operation has nothing to do with the user and his/her ability to recover from the so-called &quot;error&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="11" relname="span"> -- why should the user be involved at all?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="13" relname="span"> It becomes annoying to see these messages that make no sense to the user.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="15" relname="span"> Good error recovery involves a clear path out of the problem.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="14" relname="span"> Most error messages are vague and uninformative.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="8" relname="span"> That long string of numbers from the illegal error message that P20 refers to a great example.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="circumstance"> (Windows 98 was not too long ago and some are still using it.)</segment>
